    {
        "text": "This definitely happened to other languages as well, e.g. to <https:\/\/translate.rx.studio\/translate\/r-project\/base-c\/es\/?checksum=7566927d3c8b4eed|Spanish> in November 2024 or <https:\/\/translate.rx.studio\/translate\/r-project\/base-r-gui\/pt_BR\/?checksum=5026e946cb492440|Brazilian Portuguese> in December 2023, but during later rebase events the strings didn't get broken again. Some of the breakage wasn't noticed and still remains (<https:\/\/translate.rx.studio\/translate\/r-project\/stats-c\/es\/?checksum=0b596e99a6a459ec|Spanish, August 2023>; <https:\/\/translate.rx.studio\/translate\/r-project\/base-c\/es\/?checksum=d98699aab09a56fb|Spanish, November 2024>; <https:\/\/translate.rx.studio\/translate\/r-project\/tools-r\/de\/?checksum=30ea362a301be157|German, August 2025>; <https:\/\/translate.rx.studio\/translate\/r-project\/utils-r\/pl\/?checksum=b5f1f84e73cdbbc9|Polish, March 2026>). It looks like Spanish was hit the hardest overall.\n\nI'm attaching an approximate list of 363 likely rebase-\"downgraded\" translations based on a few heuristics (latest update was from the repository, not by a translator on Weblate AND the string differs from the previous one AND it had been previously encountered).\n\n(By the way, why rebase translation repo instead of merging? I have a suspicion that the way rebasing causes O(N) conflicts every time the string changes upstream may be part of the problem here.)",
